Title : Redco Pakistan Limited cricket team
Text : '''Redco Pakistan Limited''' were a [[first-class cricket]] team sponsored by the Pakistan branch of Redco International.<ref>[http://www.redcogroup.com Redco website]</ref> They played in the 1999-2000 season, competing in the [[Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]].

==First-class playing record==
After a narrow first-innings victory in the final of Grade II of the [[Patron's Trophy]] in 1998-99,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/184/184160.html Pakistan Air Force v REDCO Pakistan Limited 1998-99]</ref> Redco Pakistan Limited were promoted to first-class status for the 1999-2000 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy.

Captained by [[Hasnain Qayyum]], who scored 614 runs at an average of 51.16,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Quaid-e-Azam_Trophy_1999-00/REDCO_Pakistan_Limited_Batting.html Redco batting averages 1999-2000]</ref> Redco played 10 matches, winning three, losing one and drawing six, and finishing sixth out of 12 in Pool B of the Quaid-e-Azam Trophy.

[[Naumanullah]] made the most runs: 642 at 71.33 with three centuries. The highest score was 213 by [[Rafatullah Mohmand]] in an innings victory over [[Faisalabad cricket team|Faisalabad]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/68/68720.html Faisalabad v Redco Pakistan Limited 1999-2000]</ref> The leading bowler was [[Imran Tahir]], who took 43 wickets at 22.20, with best innings figures of 8 for 76 against [[Karachi cricket teams|Karachi Blues]],<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/68/68849.html Redco Pakistan Limited v Karachi Blues 1999-2000]</ref> and best match figures of 10 for 79 a week later against [[Peshawar cricket team|Peshawar]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/68/68887.html Redco Pakistan Limited v Peshawar 1999-2000]</ref>

==Limited-overs record==
They won their first five matches in the [[List A cricket|limited-overs]] competition in 1999-2000, losing only in the final.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Tissot_Cup_1999-00.html Tissot Cup 1999-2000]</ref> [[Bazid Khan]] made 304 runs at 60.80 with four fifties.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Tissot_Cup_1999-00/REDCO_Pakistan_Limited_Batting.html REDCO Pakistan Limited batting, Tissot Cup 1999-2000]</ref>

